Okay, so I'm working on a project called the Open Source Observatory which is managed by the European Commission and it is...

2
0:00:18.000 --> 0:00:34.000
That should not be blue. Oh well. So I'm working on OSOR. The general goals of OSOR are to help the Free Software community,

3
0:00:34.000 --> 0:00:42.000
in particular in public administrations, for them to use free software. So we have a bunch of projects going at the same time.

4
0:00:42.000 --> 0:00:48.000
We have a website, the Open Source Observatory, OSOR, where we publish free software and open source news.

5
0:00:48.000 --> 0:00:53.000
We have a knowledge centre where we're gathering information on case studies of countries that are using free software.

6
0:00:53.000 --> 0:01:00.000
We have intelligence reports on who in each country is involved in different parts of free software.

7
0:01:00.000 --> 0:01:06.000
We have summaries of all the policies that they have in place. We organise community events.

8
0:01:06.000 --> 0:01:15.000
So this year we will organise three workshops and three webinars. And from each of these workshops and webinars we will be producing a report.

9
0:01:15.000 --> 0:01:21.000
And then the latest project we've taken on is that we're going to compile these reports together into a handbook at the end of the year.

10
0:01:21.000 --> 0:01:27.000
And this is going to be kind of best practices on how to use free software in public administrations.

11
0:01:27.000 --> 0:01:31.000
So we'll be looking at different policies that people have in place. Do they work?

12
0:01:31.000 --> 0:01:39.000
The folks will be on finding experts that have already gotten free software into use on desktops and servers and services in public administrations.

13
0:01:39.000 --> 0:01:42.000
We're going to look at all the projects, the problems that they've encountered.

14
0:01:42.000 --> 0:01:47.000
And we're going to try and find the solutions that they've found for all these different problems.

15
0:01:47.000 --> 0:02:06.000
But as part of the OSOR work, we also try and get information out to the free software community to help people interact with how the European Commission is working on all these regulations that are going to affect the free software community.

16
0:02:06.000 --> 0:02:20.000
So this is part of the, there is a procedure for gathering input and doing calls for evidence, but the Commission also works through people like myself to find the free software community where you are.

17
0:02:20.000 --> 0:02:30.000
And then you bring the information, collect feedback and try and get people to contribute into the process of making these new regulations.

18
0:02:30.000 --> 0:02:38.000
So in particular today, I'm going to talk about interactive Eurobact. Now, because we had a change in the schedule, I've got a bit of extra time.

19
0:02:38.000 --> 0:02:45.000
So what I want to do is I want to make this more of an interactive session. Not the first half. The first half is going to be me reading slides.

20
0:02:45.000 --> 0:02:48.000
But the second half is where I would like to get input from everyone here.

21
0:02:48.000 --> 0:02:52.000
And so what we're doing is I'm going to present the Interoperable Eurobact.

22
0:02:52.000 --> 0:03:01.000
And we're going to, I'd like to discuss then how something like an Interoperable Eurobact can help the free software open source community.

23
0:03:01.000 --> 0:03:11.000
And then in what way can the community and the Commission and the various bodies that are created by this act, how can they all collaborate to work together?

24
0:03:11.000 --> 0:03:14.000
So in general, interoperability.

25
0:03:14.000 --> 0:03:24.000
The idea is to help governments and computer systems to interoperate and share data. This often happens at a national level already.

26
0:03:24.000 --> 0:03:30.000
It's already difficult at that stage, but the Interoperable Eurobact is going to work on this at the European level.

27
0:03:30.000 --> 0:03:41.000
And so the type of problems is trying to solve are, for example, very simple problems like reserving a parking space for your car once you travel into the next country across the border.

28
0:03:41.000 --> 0:03:44.000
And you have to type in the registration plate of your car.

29
0:03:44.000 --> 0:03:51.000
If the registration plate isn't in the standard format, then that system may not allow you to reserve a parking space.

30
0:03:51.000 --> 0:03:54.000
A little bit more complicated, something like hospital beds.

31
0:03:54.000 --> 0:04:01.000
So the idea is that if a Belgian hospital phones a French hospital and asks, do you have a bed free?

32
0:04:01.000 --> 0:04:03.000
And France says, yes, we have one bed.

33
0:04:03.000 --> 0:04:08.000
Then a Dutch hospital phones the same French hospital and they say, do you have bed free?

34
0:04:08.000 --> 0:04:12.000
Well, what is the answer? Is it one or zero or is it somewhere between the two?

35
0:04:12.000 --> 0:04:20.000
And so the whole idea is that these the idea of data sharing and trying to get all these hospital systems to work together is generally more complicated than expected.

36
0:04:20.000 --> 0:04:28.000
You have to have either a reservation system or a priority system, which is understandable to all the other 27 member states.

37
0:04:28.000 --> 0:04:30.000
So these things get pretty complicated.

38
0:04:30.000 --> 0:04:43.000
The member states generally managed to get this to work on their own systems because there's a government at the top that can tell the hospitals, you know, please have a system that works with all these other systems or make sure that you can interoperate.

39
0:04:43.000 --> 0:04:51.000
The European Union can't do that because the European Union doesn't have authority over the hospitals of Belgium and the hospitals of France and hospitals of the Netherlands.

40
0:04:51.000 --> 0:04:54.000
So the European Union can't tell the hospitals what to do.

41
0:04:54.000 --> 0:05:14.000
So the Interoperable Europe Act is about setting a standard that will apply to the member states for how they will interoperate with it or they how they will interact with their hospitals and systems for reserving car parking spaces and other things to make all these systems work across borders as well as they are working within the borders already.

42
0:05:14.000 --> 0:05:16.000
So that's an interoperability.

43
0:05:16.000 --> 0:05:18.000
And then there's also the idea of data sharing.

44
0:05:18.000 --> 0:05:23.000
And so this is the third example of when a city city wants to introduce some kind of traffic management system.

45
0:05:23.000 --> 0:05:29.000
They may find that other cities across Europe have already done something similar and they might find a good example.

46
0:05:29.000 --> 0:05:46.000
But will that data be available to them or will the the system that has been created by that other member state, will that be available to this city so they can use the same framework and so they can learn from the same information that the successful city learned from.

47
0:05:46.000 --> 0:05:56.000
So the current situation is that we have the interoperable European interoperability framework. This is the main piece of legislation.

48
0:05:56.000 --> 0:05:58.000
The that's been updated a few times.

49
0:05:58.000 --> 0:06:00.000
The most recent version was updated in 2017.

50
0:06:00.000 --> 0:06:07.000
The main difference between this and what is being proposed at the moment is the 2017 text is non-binding.

51
0:06:07.000 --> 0:06:20.000
So this is works on the goodwill and cooperation between member states, but it's not that no member states are not required to do anything by this through this system.

52
0:06:20.000 --> 0:06:24.000
So then there are also other informal ways that cooperation has been helped.

53
0:06:24.000 --> 0:06:28.000
There is the Digital Europe program and the join up platform.

54
0:06:28.000 --> 0:06:34.000
So the join up platform is a website where, for example, the open source observatory is situated.

55
0:06:34.000 --> 0:06:46.000
And this is a place where a lot of different projects from the European Commission are available online and they can share solutions and code repositories and general information or articles.

56
0:06:46.000 --> 0:06:50.000
And this is another way that interoperability has been helped.

57
0:06:50.000 --> 0:06:58.000
And that's but again, it's a voluntary idea because it's it's making information available in the hope that people will use it if they'd like to use it.

58
0:06:58.000 --> 0:07:10.000
And then the third way that interoperability has been worked on already is through this informal network of CEOs from the member states and the expert group on interoperability of European public services.

59
0:07:10.000 --> 0:07:19.000
So this is the human side getting individuals to talk to each other and trying to get interoperability to happen that way.

60
0:07:19.000 --> 0:07:31.000
So this is useful, but the it could be a lot more useful in terms of making the cooperation between all these cities and member states more efficient.

61
0:07:31.000 --> 0:07:46.000
It could be good to lay down a set of minimum interoperability specifications, ways of sharing data, not just formats, but the technical specifications for how data will be shared and communicated.

62
0:07:46.000 --> 0:08:03.000
And then the third option part is the idea of a binding requirement to have interoperability by default as an approach when designing new systems and also to promote the promote designing systems that are interoperable.

63
0:08:03.000 --> 0:08:18.000
So the European Commission has been gathering information and this is the standard procedure when making any regulation. They do a call for evidence, a call for input. They work on impact assessments. They talk to their own research centers, which is the JRC, the Joint Research Centre.

64
0:08:18.000 --> 0:08:22.000
And part of that is the CPS, the Centre for European Policy Studies.

65
0:08:22.000 --> 0:08:33.000
They've gone through these systems. They put together, they did online consultations and they've got 134 for the impact assessment, 112 replies for the European Interoperability Framework.

66
0:08:33.000 --> 0:08:39.000
They also performed then interviews with specialists or stakeholders in all these domains.

67
0:08:39.000 --> 0:08:52.000
And then presentations like this are the little annex on this because from all this they've talked to a load of experts, but has anyone in the room been involved in any of these procedures?

68
0:08:52.000 --> 0:08:56.000
One. Okay. That's two. Fantastic.

69
0:08:56.000 --> 0:09:13.000
So for everyone else in the room, this is a way that the European Commission, this presentation is a way the European Commission is trying to get information to the public and to the free software community in particular so that people can participate and be aware of what can be participated in.

70
0:09:13.000 --> 0:09:19.000
So the Interoperable Eurobact is not the only piece of legislation that is currently enforced or being worked on.

71
0:09:19.000 --> 0:09:27.000
We already have the single digital gateway where member states have an automated cross border exchange of documents.

72
0:09:27.000 --> 0:09:35.000
There is the Open Data Directive, which is for the European Interoperability Framework for designing technical solutions for the reuse of documents.

73
0:09:35.000 --> 0:09:40.000
The European Strategy for Data, which is about interoperability of data.

74
0:09:40.000 --> 0:09:52.000
The Data Governance Act, which is cross sector data supporting the Interoperability framework principles and the core vocabularies of these.

75
0:09:52.000 --> 0:10:01.000
The digitalization of justice, which is a general trend, which is to make the IT tools used by the justice systems interoperable with each other.

76
0:10:01.000 --> 0:10:06.000
And then there are two pieces of legislation that are currently still going through the legislative process.

77
0:10:06.000 --> 0:10:16.000
One is the Data Act, which is on interoperability of data among different sectors within Europe.

78
0:10:16.000 --> 0:10:19.000
And then we also have the Regulation on Digital Identity.

79
0:10:19.000 --> 0:10:23.000
And this is where member states have to have digital identity wallets.

80
0:10:23.000 --> 0:10:30.000
And this is to create a standard so this can interoperate between the different member states.

81
0:10:30.000 --> 0:10:41.000
So the European Interoperability Act will be beside or in some cases on top of these existing pieces of legislation.

82
0:10:41.000 --> 0:10:53.000
So the general goals are to create a consistent approach to Europe interoperability and to policymaking across the member states,

83
0:10:53.000 --> 0:10:56.000
to establish an interoperability governance structure.

84
0:10:56.000 --> 0:11:01.000
So this I'll discuss a little bit later how exactly that will work and how people here cannot be involved in that.

85
0:11:01.000 --> 0:11:09.000
But this is the second, besides the technical issues of how to how technically interoperability should happen.

86
0:11:09.000 --> 0:11:17.000
There's also the governance of all these different structures that will be created and how that governance should interact with users and experts.

87
0:11:17.000 --> 0:11:29.000
Then the last part is the idea of creating an ecosystem, a general environment for the EU's public sector so that people can contribute to interoperable solutions

88
0:11:29.000 --> 0:11:33.000
and people are aware of what interoperable solutions exist already.

89
0:11:33.000 --> 0:11:39.000
And so this innovation can happen in a collaborative way so that there is more reuse of code.

90
0:11:39.000 --> 0:11:47.000
Because we've seen quite a lot of countries now have gotten to the stage of accepting free software as a good idea

91
0:11:47.000 --> 0:11:50.000
and they publish a lot of source code for the things they're doing.

92
0:11:50.000 --> 0:11:56.000
But we don't yet see a lot of instances where a city from one member state will copy a solution from another member state

93
0:11:56.000 --> 0:11:59.000
and start even contributing back to that solution.

94
0:11:59.000 --> 0:12:13.000
So this is the next step in terms of collaboration and making a good use of free software is the idea of an ecosystem and getting the collaborative innovation to happen.

95
0:12:13.000 --> 0:12:22.000
So inside the Interoperable Europe Act there are these six chapters. I'm going to focus on three of them.

96
0:12:22.000 --> 0:12:36.000
The general idea is that it is a mandatory interoperability that comes with assessments and support and solutions that already exist and encouraging people to create new solutions.

97
0:12:36.000 --> 0:12:42.000
But these pieces of text are from the actual Interoperable Europe Act.

98
0:12:42.000 --> 0:12:47.000
So at the moment what we have is the European Commission has published their proposal.

99
0:12:47.000 --> 0:12:57.000
This then gets handed to the European Parliament which are the directly elected members of the Parliament there.

100
0:12:57.000 --> 0:13:04.000
So these are often the easiest to interact with for people who are not too involved in the legislative process.

101
0:13:04.000 --> 0:13:11.000
It is also handed to the European Council which is the ministers or the governments of the member states.

102
0:13:11.000 --> 0:13:21.000
So this is a second group that will be looking at the text from the Commission and they will think about whether to accept it as is or whether they should propose amendments.

103
0:13:21.000 --> 0:13:26.000
So this means the legislative proposal for creating the Interoperable Europe Act is still ongoing.

104
0:13:26.000 --> 0:13:34.000
It's still something that it's actually in the fairly early stages even and it's still something where people can get involved and that's what I'm hoping to facilitate here.

105
0:13:34.000 --> 0:13:41.000
So this is one piece of text from the current proposal for an Interoperable Europe Act.

106
0:13:41.000 --> 0:13:51.000
This is the share and reuse requirement and it is one of the parts that definitely directly will affect the free and open source software community.

107
0:13:51.000 --> 0:14:05.000
So what is probably interesting in this is the idea that they've created a piece of text to encourage the sharing of solutions.

108
0:14:05.000 --> 0:14:19.000
And so this is what we are quite used to in the free software community but their definition or the way they describe this is that if the solutions, which solutions will generally mean software,

109
0:14:19.000 --> 0:14:27.000
solutions shall be made available to any such entity that requests it and shall include documented source code.

110
0:14:27.000 --> 0:14:37.000
So that's their current definition of what it should look like to have member states working together on solutions such as software.

111
0:14:37.000 --> 0:14:47.000
So this is what the Parliament will now look at and the Council and for we can interact with the Parliament and the Council to decide can this be improved?

112
0:14:47.000 --> 0:14:58.000
Should this be adopted as is or if other people want to change it we can give our opinion on whether it should be kept or whether other changes should be included.

113
0:14:58.000 --> 0:15:03.000
So this is one part that I'd like to get some input on at the end of this session.

114
0:15:03.000 --> 0:15:10.000
So if you have any comments on how that whether this definition is ideal or not, that would be interesting.

115
0:15:10.000 --> 0:15:19.000
The second part is in Chapter 2, which is quite a long chapter but I've only included a small amount here.

116
0:15:19.000 --> 0:15:38.000
Maybe the most interesting points are that there will be the creation of the Interoperable Europe portal, which is a place where it will be possible to share solutions and data and to create some kind of interaction between people who are interested in this topic and to increase transparency of how work is being done on this.

117
0:15:38.000 --> 0:15:47.000
One interesting part of Article 8 is that there is somewhat a definition of what free software such open source is.

118
0:15:47.000 --> 0:16:05.000
So it says here, I'll highlight some bits, an open source license means a license whereby the reuse of software is permitted for all specified uses in a unilateral declaration by the right holder and where the source codes of the software are made available for users.

119
0:16:05.000 --> 0:16:16.000
So this is the first time I've seen free software or open source license being defined in a European regulation.

120
0:16:16.000 --> 0:16:28.000
Once again, this is something that we will have to think about and accept input on and decide whether this is the way it should be defined and or are there improvements that could be made.

121
0:16:28.000 --> 0:16:43.000
The second most interesting part in Article 3 is that the EUPL, the European Union Public License, is suggested as the default license for public administrations publishing source code solutions.

122
0:16:43.000 --> 0:16:55.000
The EUPL for, I'll just present briefly, is a valid free software license. It's approved by Free Software Foundation and Open Source Initiative as well.

123
0:16:55.000 --> 0:17:04.000
It is a somewhat copy left license. So the EUPL itself includes a copy left clause.

124
0:17:04.000 --> 0:17:12.000
So if you're using the EUPL and you publish software and somebody else modifies it, they also have to publish their source code.

125
0:17:12.000 --> 0:17:15.000
So it's quite a traditional copy left in that sense.

126
0:17:15.000 --> 0:17:30.000
But it has a compatibility clause and the compatibility clause says if you're merging EUPL source code with another project under a license that's listed in the annex, you can change the EUPL license to the license of that project.

127
0:17:30.000 --> 0:17:35.000
So this means, for example, the GPLv3 is one of the licenses in the annex.

128
0:17:35.000 --> 0:17:44.000
So if you have a GPLv3 project and an EUPL project, you can merge the two and distribute the whole thing under GPLv3.

129
0:17:44.000 --> 0:17:57.000
So this is one way, a very positive, a very, very useful clause that they've inserted to work on license compatibility, which between copy left licenses is always difficult.

130
0:17:57.000 --> 0:18:04.000
On the other hand, there are also licenses in the annex of the EUPL which are not copy left licenses or not strong copy left licenses.

131
0:18:04.000 --> 0:18:12.000
And so it's possible that the EUPL software would be merged with a software project which is under a non-strong copy left license.

132
0:18:12.000 --> 0:18:16.000
And then the whole would be distributed without being under strong copy left.

133
0:18:16.000 --> 0:18:25.000
So in one sense, it's copy left license, but also there's no guarantee that downstream uses of that code will remain copy left.

134
0:18:25.000 --> 0:18:36.000
So that is the most unique part of the EUPL, I believe.

135
0:18:36.000 --> 0:18:54.000
And a second aspect that is quite interesting of the EUPL is that it has been translated into all the official languages of the European Union, which is quite useful because some member states or cities have requirements in their law saying that they can only sign contracts that are under their own official languages.

136
0:18:54.000 --> 0:19:10.000
So if there's any difficulty with getting software put under, for example, GPLv3, because the GPLv3 is in English, there's always the option of getting the software published under EUPL and it can be kept under EUPL or can be later converted into GPLv3.

137
0:19:10.000 --> 0:19:17.000
So that is the EUPL. It's getting more and more use at the moment.

138
0:19:17.000 --> 0:19:35.000
So here's just a map with a few examples of member states that are currently using the EUPL. But once the Interoperable Europe Act comes into force, if the current wording is kept, the EUPL will presumably be used by a lot more member states and local governments.

139
0:19:35.000 --> 0:19:41.000
And so it is a license that we're going to be seeing more and more use of.

140
0:19:41.000 --> 0:19:52.000
So those, the Chapter 1 and Chapter 2 are the technical aspects of the EUPL. Then Chapter 4 contains the governance structure.

141
0:19:52.000 --> 0:20:00.000
So this part is how interaction is going to be done with experts and with member states.

142
0:20:00.000 --> 0:20:08.000
And so the Interoperable Europe Act proposes making an Interoperable Europe board and then an Interoperable Europe community.

143
0:20:08.000 --> 0:20:15.000
So these two will work together, the board having a more executive function, the community having more of an input role.

144
0:20:15.000 --> 0:20:26.000
They will both interact with national authorities and national authorities will be required to create national assessment bodies and there will be interoperability coordinators.

145
0:20:26.000 --> 0:20:38.000
The details of how all this will work might look a little complicated, might be a bit complicated as well, but is also not completely defined at the moment.

146
0:20:38.000 --> 0:20:49.000
So there have been statements at conferences to say that the Free Software Community will be included in the Interoperable Europe Community.

147
0:20:49.000 --> 0:21:00.000
And the fact that this has been explicitly mentioned by high ranking people in the Commission means that it should be quite a real role.

148
0:21:00.000 --> 0:21:07.000
Which means as a community we now have to think about how do we want to be involved in an Interoperable Europe community.

149
0:21:07.000 --> 0:21:11.000
If we are to have representatives, how do we choose these?

150
0:21:11.000 --> 0:21:21.000
If we are to work with the Interoperable Europe board, what exactly would we be requesting or what would we be suggesting?

151
0:21:21.000 --> 0:21:36.000
And so this is where I will soon come to the interactive part because this will be up to us to think about how can an interoperability framework help the free and open source software community.

152
0:21:36.000 --> 0:21:42.000
How can it help the software itself in terms of data formats?

153
0:21:42.000 --> 0:21:53.000
What can we do to make sure the data formats and the systems that use them are systems that can be used by existing Free Software solutions?

154
0:21:53.000 --> 0:22:04.000
Or if we are developing new solutions, what do we need to make sure that these things can all be made use of by the Free Software and Open Source community?

155
0:22:04.000 --> 0:22:12.000
So that is the general idea of the Interoperable Europe Act.

156
0:22:12.000 --> 0:22:23.000
It will have all these positive outcomes, legal certainty of course, more innovation, more agility for public administrations and connected digital public services.

157
0:22:23.000 --> 0:22:35.000
But the reason I'm giving this talk here today is because I would like to have your suggestions.

158
0:22:35.000 --> 0:22:43.000
Possibly from the people who have already been involved in these various procedures, but do you have a microphone for questions?

